<p>Just really quickly, since my team will be using command based programming that fits the subsystem-command setup, how would I organize the file (placing it where) and how would I go about calling the periodic method from RobotContainer?</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2025-01-07T16:50:41.166Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":93,"readers_count":92,"score":33.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":479705,"topic_slug":"command-based-programming-for-limelight","display_username":"Daniel McLaughlin","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":33946,"username":"Amicus1","name":"Amicus1","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/a9adbd/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":69324,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/command-based-programming-for-limelight/479705/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3474266,"name":"Amicus1","username":"Amicus1","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/a9adbd/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-01-07T19:31:29.459Z","cooked":"<p>Move the contents of Update.periodic into Limelight.periodic after what you already have in there, where you’ve already collected the data from the limelight.</p>
<p>For calling the periodic method, first you have to make a RobotContainer.periodic and call that from Robot.robotPeriodic. Next you call Limelight.periodic from RobotContainer.periodic.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2025-01-07T19:31:29.459Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":75,"readers_count":74,"score":20.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":479705,"topic_slug":"command-based-programming-for-limelight","display_username":"Amicus1","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":69324,"username":"Pieyama_Pieman","name":"Daniel McLaughlin","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/pieyama_pieman/{size}/242065_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":33946,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"6995A/Choreo/Monologue"},"post_url":"/t/command-based-programming-for-limelight/479705/4","custom_user_title":"6995A/Choreo/Monologue","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3474450,"name":"","username":"C3434","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/c/ee59a6/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-01-07T21:19:55.426Z","cooked":"<p>Although you already have an approved answer, if you are wondering how you would implement your original code there are a few things that you’d have to change.</p>
<p>Firstly, everything in your periodic is a local variable, so it’s inaccessible outside of your periodic. I’d recommend adding get functions, like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public double getX() {
    return NetworkTableInstance.getDefault()
               .getTable("limelight")
               .getEntry("tx")
               .getDouble(0.0);
}
</code></pre>
<p>Next, your Updator command is missing your limelight subsystem. You don’t necessarily have to add the limelight as a requirement in this case, as you are just getting data from the subsystem but not controlling it. Though this example will include it.<br>
The new Updator Command (Not including imports):</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public class Updator extends Command {
  private final Limelight limelight;

  public Updator(Limelight limelight) {
    this.limelight = limelight;

    addRequirements(limelight);
  }

  @Override
  public void execute() {
    SmartDashboard.putNumber("TargetHoriz", limelight.getX());
    SmartDashboard.putNumber("TargetVert", limelight.getY());
    SmartDashboard.putNumber("TargetArea", limelight.getA());
    SmartDashboard.putBoolean("CanSee?", limelight.getV());
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>In order to handle this in the robot container you would do the following (assuming you already have your limelight constructed in your robot container)</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">limelight.addDefaultCommand(new Updator(limelight));
</code></pre>
<p>Or if you didn’t include the addRequirements() earlier you could just schedule the command directly</p>
<p>Another thing I would recommend is something to make the limelight subsystem expandable, so you could have multiple limelights in the future if you want. To do this you would pass through the limelight name as a parameter to your limelight subsystem, then save it and use it in place of your “limelight” string when accessing your table</p>
<p>Though for what you are doing with this command, I would recommend just putting it in your subsystem’s periodic, you could even use your get functions for simpler code.</p>
